<!-- ── FAQ ── -->
<section class="content-section reveal">
  <h2>FAQ</h2>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      What are the 2025 Roth IRA contribution limits?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        For 2025, you can contribute up to <strong>$7,000</strong> per year if you're under 50, or <strong>$8,000</strong> if you're 50 or older (the extra $1,000 is a catch-up contribution). These limits apply across all your IRAs combined — if you have both a Roth and Traditional IRA, your total contributions to both cannot exceed $7,000/$8,000.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      Are there income limits for contributing to a Roth IRA?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        Yes. For 2025, single filers can make a full contribution if their modified adjusted gross income (MAGI) is under $150,000. Contributions phase out between $150,000 and $165,000, and you cannot contribute directly above $165,000. For married filing jointly, the phase-out range is $236,000 to $246,000. If you exceed these limits, you may still be able to use a backdoor Roth strategy.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      Roth IRA vs Traditional IRA — which is better?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        It depends on your current tax rate versus your expected retirement tax rate. <strong>Roth IRA</strong>: you contribute after-tax dollars and withdraw tax-free in retirement — best if you expect to be in a higher tax bracket later. <strong>Traditional IRA</strong>: you may deduct contributions now and pay taxes on withdrawals in retirement — best if you expect a lower bracket later. If you're early in your career and in a low bracket, Roth usually wins. Use the "Roth vs Traditional" tab to compare with your actual numbers.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">
      What is a backdoor Roth IRA?
      <span class="faq-chevron">▼</span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-answer">
      <div class="faq-answer-inner">
        A backdoor Roth is a legal strategy for high earners who exceed the Roth IRA income limits. You contribute to a <strong>Traditional IRA</strong> (non-deductible), then <strong>convert</strong> it to a Roth IRA. There's no income limit on conversions. The key: if you have no existing pre-tax IRA balances, you'll owe little to no tax on the conversion. If you do have pre-tax IRA funds, the pro-rata rule applies — a portion of each conversion is taxable. Consult a tax advisor for your specific situation.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

